      Coinbase
   =20
 =20

I don=E2=80=99t know what the US Securities and Exchange Commission=E2=80=
=99s   Wells notice to Coinbase Global Inc. is about. The  notice itself=C2=
=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0a letter that the SEC sends saying that it intends to bri=
ng an enforcement action =E2=80=94 is quite bare-bones and doesn=E2=80=99t =
say what the issue is, though presumably the SEC has given Coinbase some mo=
re detail over the phone.=C2=A0Quite possibly the problem is something fair=
ly contained, like, =E2=80=9Crecently=C2=A0you launched a new product that =
we think violates the securities laws, so we are going to bring an enforcem=
ent action focused on that product.=E2=80=9D
On the other hand if the problem is, like, =E2=80=9Cyou are operating a cry=
pto exchange, and we think that operating a crypto exchange is illegal, so =
we are going to bring an enforcement action to stop you from doing that,=E2=
=80=9D I would not be entirely=C2=A0stunned either. I mean, it=E2=80=99s pr=
obably not quite=C2=A0that broad. But the SEC has  made it clear,   over an=
d   over again, that it thinks almost all crypto tokens (except Bitcoin, Et=
hereum
  [1]
=C2=A0and maybe a handful of others) are =E2=80=9Csecurities=E2=80=9D withi=
n the meaning of US securities law, and if you run an exchange for trading =
securities you need to register it with the SEC and comply with a lot of ru=
les.
  [2]

Coinbase does not=C2=A0run an SEC-registered securities exchange, but it of=
fers trading in a few hundred crypto tokens. Coinbase thinks that none of t=
hem are securities, but what are the chances that the SEC agrees? Well, we =
happen to know the answer to that: Last year the SEC brought a case against=
 a former Coinbase employee accusing him of insider trading on some tokens =
that Coinbase listed. The SEC can only bring insider trading cases about se=
curities,=C2=A0and it argued=C2=A0that the tokens the guy traded were secur=
ities. I=C2=A0tweeted at the time: =E2=80=9CThis is a weird way for the SEC=
 to say that Coinbase is running an illegal securities exchange?=E2=80=9D S=
ending Coinbase a Wells notice threatening to sue it for running an illegal=
 securities exchange would be a more normal way to say it, and here we are.
Taking a step back, though, if the SEC thinks that 90% of Coinbase=E2=80=99=
s crypto listings are illegal =E2=80=A6=C2=A0what took it so long? Coinbase=
 has been running a crypto exchange  since 2012, matching hundreds of billi=
ons of dollars of trades and making billions of dollars of revenue. It has =
been, as crypto exchanges go, pretty compliance-focused, getting various re=
gulatory licenses (including an SEC broker-dealer license) and publishing a=
udited financial statements. It is a US public company, listed on the Nasda=
q; it went public in a direct listing in=C2=A02021. If Coinbase is running =
an illegal securities exchange, it has been doing it out in the open for an=
 awfully long time. Weird for the SEC to only notice now.
And so Coinbase Chief Executive Officer Brian Armstrong=C2=A0tweeted about =
the Wells notice:
  [3]

Two years ago the SEC reviewed our business in detail and approved Coinbase=
 to go public. Our S1 clearly explained our asset listing process and inclu=
ded 57 references to staking. Coinbase runs a rigorous asset review process=
 and has rejected more than 90% of assets that have applied to be listed on=
 the platform.
And Coinbase Chief Legal Officer Paul Grewal  wrote a blog post:

The SEC staff told us they have identified potential violations of securiti=
es law, but little more. We asked the SEC specifically to identify which as=
sets on our platforms they believe may be securities, and they declined to =
do so. Today=E2=80=99s Wells notice also comes after Coinbase provided mult=
iple proposals to the SEC about registration over the course of months, all=
 of which the SEC ultimately refused to respond to. =E2=80=A6
The Wells notice comes out of the investigation that we disclosed last summ=
er. Shortly after that investigation began, the SEC asked us if we would be=
 interested in discussing a potential resolution that would include registe=
ring some portion of our business with the SEC. We said absolutely yes. Spe=
cifically, the SEC asked us to provide our views on what a registration pat=
h for Coinbase could look like =E2=80=93 because there is no existing way f=
or a crypto exchange to register. We developed and proposed two different r=
egistration models. We spent millions of dollars on legal support to build =
these proposals and repeatedly asked for the SEC=E2=80=99s feedback. We got=
 none. We also reiterated that we stand by our listings process =E2=80=93 w=
e don=E2=80=99t list securities today =E2=80=93 and repeatedly invited the =
SEC to raise any questions about any asset at all on our platform. They rai=
sed none. =E2=80=A6
Regulatory uncertainty in the crypto industry is getting worse. Instead of =
developing a regulatory framework for crypto, the SEC is continuing to regu=
late by enforcement only.=C2=A0

I sympathize with all of this, and I have   written similar  things. It is =
truly hard to fit the particular features of crypto into the existing US sy=
stem for regulating securities, and a conscientious securities regulator wi=
th an interest in crypto regulation would sit down and write rules explaini=
ng=C2=A0how=C2=A0a project could register its crypto securities, how a cryp=
to exchange could list crypto securities, etc. (Obviously Coinbase=E2=80=99=
s proposal to write those rules=C2=A0for=C2=A0the SEC is kind of self-inter=
ested, but sure in general regulation proceeds with industry input.)
On the other hand I think that the SEC=E2=80=99s response is straightforwar=
d and obvious:
=09There absolutely are existing, reasonably clear rules about how you regi=
ster securities.=09Yes, you=E2=80=99re right, it=E2=80=99s impossible for c=
rypto tokens to follow those rules.=09Oh well! Guess that means crypto exch=
anges are illegal.

The position of Coinbase =E2=80=94=C2=A0and of the crypto industry more bro=
adly =E2=80=94=C2=A0is =E2=80=9Clook, SEC, if you want to have a flourishin=
g system of legally compliant, safe, trustworthy crypto assets, you will ne=
ed to work with us a little bit to write new rules,=E2=80=9D and the positi=
on of the SEC is =E2=80=9Cno, we don=E2=80=99t want that, we want all of yo=
u to go away forever.=E2=80=9D If Bernie Madoff came to the SEC and said =
=E2=80=9Cif you want a higher class of more trustworthy Ponzi schemes, you =
will need to write a few new rules adapting the disclosure regime to Ponzi =
schemes,=E2=80=9D the SEC would have said =E2=80=9Cno we absolutely do not =
want that, we want=C2=A0much less Ponzi scheming, and we certainly do not w=
ant to give our=C2=A0approval=C2=A0to Ponzi schemes by writing rules for th=
em.=E2=80=9D One gets the sense the attitude to crypto is similar.
On the other hand Coinbase is an SEC-registered public company with an SEC-=
registered broker-dealer license! The approval is kind of already there! Th=
e SEC=E2=80=99s=C2=A0attitude=C2=A0to crypto is extremely negative, but it =
is only slowly getting around to doing anything about it =E2=80=94=C2=A0and=
