The   basic lessons of   the Silicon Valley Bank failure might be:
=09Some number of US regional banks are apparently insolvent, if you compar=
e the market values of their assets (lots of fixed-rate loans and bonds tha=
t lost value as interest rates rose) with their liabilities (deposits, etc.=
).=09Mostly this is a weird uncomfortable fact of life in banking in a rate=
-hiking cycle, and everyone politely ignores it.=09Sometimes people notice =
and that=E2=80=99s bad.

If people notice, there=E2=80=99s a bank run, the bank has to sell its asse=
ts to raise money to pay out depositors, the assets sell for less than the =
deposits, and the bank goes bust. But if no one notices then it is mostly a=
 profitability problem. The bank=E2=80=99s cost of deposits goes up, its in=
come on investments does not go up as fast (because it has lots of long-ter=
m fixed-rate assets), and its net interest margins get squeezed. Maybe it l=
oses money. But it doesn=E2=80=99t have to=C2=A0sell=C2=A0the assets all at=
 once; it can wait for them to mature, and then reinvest the money in highe=
r-yielding assets and it=E2=80=99s fine. The insolvent bank can zombie alon=
g for a while and work its way out of the hole.
When Silicon Valley Bank failed, the essential regulatory response was to  =
 double down on this mechanism. Now banks that have liquidity problems can =
use a new Federal Reserve program, the Bank Term Financing Program, to borr=
ow money against their long-term bonds; crucially, they can borrow against =
the=C2=A0face amount=C2=A0of those bonds instead of the=C2=A0market value. =
If you have $100 of long-term 1% bonds that are now worth $85, you can borr=
ow $100 against them, meaning that you can use those $85 of bonds to pay ou=
t $100 of fleeing deposits. This is terrible for your=C2=A0profitability=C2=
=A0=E2=80=94 you  pay=C2=A04.7% to the BTFP and get only 1% on the bonds, s=
o you=E2=80=99re losing 3.7% per year =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it does mean that =
you don=E2=80=99t vanish over the weekend if deposits flee. Which means the=
re=E2=80=99s not much reason for deposits to flee. So it=E2=80=99s fine.
Still it is a zombie-ish existence, being an insolvent bank. You can get by=
 with Fed liquidity support, but you are losing money on the deal. It is ha=
rd to raise capital, because the return on capital seems to be negative. It=
 is hard to find an acquirer, because the value of your assets is less than=
 your liabilities. Your regulators might=C2=A0want you to find a buyer, to =
spruce up the banking system a bit, but how does that deal work? Does the b=
uyer buy your stock for less than zero? Will shareholders accept that? Who =
provides the extra money?
Bloomberg=E2=80=99s   Max Reyes reports on First Republic Bank, which was  =
 rescued last week by an infusion of $30 billion of deposits from bigger ba=
nks, and which has been in talks about some sort of deal since SVB failed, =
but which keeps not actually doing a deal. The reason is, what deal is ther=
e to be done?

Whatever plan emerges to preserve First Republic Bank might not leave much =
for shareholders of the troubled California lender.
That=E2=80=99s because the bank=E2=80=99s tangible book value is far underw=
ater, according to Wall Street analysts, creating a capital gap of as much =
as $13.5 billion =E2=80=94 a sum that may help explain why no savior appear=
s to have stepped forward. While a government-aided deal could emerge and l=
eave the bank standing, the same won=E2=80=99t necessarily be true for stoc=
kholders.
=E2=80=9CGiven the fair value marks embedded in both its loan and securitie=
s portfolios, we find it difficult to come up with a realistic scenario whe=
re there=E2=80=99s residual value for FRC common equity holders,=E2=80=9D W=
edbush analysts led by David Chiaverini said in a March 17 note to clients,=
 which he reaffirmed by email Wednesday. =E2=80=9COur base case scenario is=
 that there would be no residual value for shareholders in either a distres=
sed M&A sale or through receivership.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6
The big hurdle is First Republic=E2=80=99s book of underwater loans and sec=
urities. Most acquirers, including banks, would have to immediately record =
those losses on their own books, which would mean a big hit to their own fi=
nancial statements. First Republic=E2=80=99s portfolio has losses of about =
$26.8 billion, leaving a negative common equity of $13 billion, Morgan Stan=
ley analysts Manan Gosalia, William Tackett and Brian Wilczynski said in a =
research note Monday.

Right now First Republic seems to be operating just fine as a bank, and its=
 stock, which represents an option on its recovery, has a positive price. A=
 buyer would apparently pay a negative price for it. The bid-ask is pretty =
wide.

