  [1] One pet theory of mine is that if you hung out with SEC Chair Gary Ge=
nsler and got a few drinks into him, he would tell you =E2=80=9Cobviously E=
thereum is a security.=E2=80=9D I have never tried this, but come on. Howev=
er, that ship has sailed and everyone agrees that, for US regulatory purpos=
es, Ethereum is not a security.


  [2] You don=E2=80=99t quite have to be a =E2=80=9Cnationally registered s=
ecurities exchange,=E2=80=9D though that helps, and SEC-registered broker-d=
ealers can operate regulated =E2=80=9Calternative trading systems=E2=80=9D =
that can look fairly exchange-like. But the regulatory burden there is not =
trivial either, and while Coinbase does have a broker-dealer registration i=
t does not meet these requirements. Coinbase  says in its risk factors: =E2=
=80=9CPlatforms that bring together purchasers and sellers to trade crypto =
assets that are securities in the United States are generally subject to re=
gistration as national securities exchanges, or must qualify for an exempti=
on, such as by being operated by a registered broker-dealer as an ATS in co=
mpliance with rules for ATSs. =E2=80=A6 Because Coinbase Spot Market, Coinb=
ase Prime and Coinbase app are not registered or licensed with the SEC or f=
oreign authorities as a broker-dealer, national securities exchange, or ATS=
 (or foreign equivalents), we only permit trading of those crypto assets fo=
r which we determine there are reasonably strong arguments to conclude that=
 the crypto asset is not a security.=E2=80=9D=20


  [3] He mentions =E2=80=9Cstaking=E2=80=9D here, which is a bit different =
from the listing of tokens that are arguably securities. The idea of stakin=
g is that customers can give Coinbase some of their non-security tokens (ma=
inly Ether) and Coinbase will stake them to validate transactions on the to=
ken=E2=80=99s blockchain and be paid staking rewards, which it will share w=
ith the customers. The SEC thinks that this *program* is a security, even i=
f the underlying token is not =E2=80=94 just like a money market mutual fun=
d is a security (you pool your money to invest in interest-earning assets) =
even if dollars are not. Last month the SEC   shut down the staking product=
 of Kraken, another crypto exchange, so it is sort of obvious that Coinbase=
=E2=80=99s staking product was next.


  [4] To be clear, TRX is  not actually listed on Coinbase, so Coinbase has=
 not taken the position that it=E2=80=99s not a security. I just mean that =
Armstrong probably sympathizes a little with Sun here.


