49bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB66370187" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Wells notice =
to Coinbase Global Inc.</a> is about. The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/30935281.265435/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuY3RmYXNzZXRzLm5=
ldC9jNWJkMHdxamM3djAvNkc1QWp0RHZScVJkaXdsaWpLRFN4RS9mMDQ5Mzk4OTA5OTE0Y2IwMz=
Y0NmQwODE5ZDdhNDhkMS8yMDIzLjAzLjIyX0NvaW5iYXNlX19JbmMuX1dlbGxzX25vdGljZS5wZ=
GY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3bcf7810" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> notice itself</a>=C2=A0=E2=
=80=94=C2=A0a letter that the SEC sends saying that it intends to bring an =
enforcement action =E2=80=94 is quite bare-bones and doesn=E2=80=99t say wh=
at the issue is, though presumably the SEC has given Coinbase some more det=
ail over the phone.=C2=A0Quite possibly the problem is something fairly con=
tained, like, =E2=80=9Crecently=C2=A0you launched a new product that we thi=
nk violates the securities laws, so we are going to bring an enforcement ac=
tion focused on that product.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand if the problem is, like, =E2=
=80=9Cyou are operating a crypto exchange, and we think that operating a cr=
ypto exchange is illegal, so we are going to bring an enforcement action to=
 stop you from doing that,=E2=80=9D I would not be <em>entirely=C2=A0</em>s=
tunned either. I mean, it=E2=80=99s probably not quite=C2=A0<em>that</em> b=
road. But the SEC has <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/30935281.265435/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJ=
zLzIwMjEtMDgtMDkvbW9uZXktc3R1ZmYtdGhlLXNlYy1oYXMtc29tZS1jcnlwdG8tY29tcGxhaW=
50cz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzIzMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY=
2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAzMjMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB429e621c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> made</a> it clear, <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30935281.265435/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYm=
xvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMTAtMTQvdGhlLXNlYy1yZWFsbHktZ=
G9lc24tdC1saWtlLWljb3M_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMyMzIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1l=
bWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMzIzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1=
tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc80abd6a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  over</a> and <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30935281.265435/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDktMDgvZ2FyeS1n=
ZW5zbGVyLXdhbnRzLXRvLXJlZ3VsYXRlLWNyeXB0bz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzIzMjNfTU9ORVlTVFV=
GRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAzMj=
MmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5c9c13fe" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
">  over</a> again, that it thinks almost all crypto tokens (except Bitcoin=
, Ethereum<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-co=
lor: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0and maybe a handful of others) are =E2=80=9Csecurities=E2=80=9D w=
ithin the meaning of US securities law, and if you run an exchange for trad=
ing securities you need to register it with the SEC and comply with a lot o=
f rules.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-colo=
r: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Coinbase does <em>not=C2=A0</em>run an SEC-reg=
istered securities exchange, but it offers trading <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30935281.265435/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY29pbmJhc2=
UuY29tL2V4cGxvcmUvcy9saXN0ZWQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfd66bc1d" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
in a few hundred crypto tokens</a>. Coinbase thinks that none of them are s=
ecurities, but what are the chances that the SEC agrees? Well, we happen to=
 know the answer to that: Last year the SEC <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/30935281.265435/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL=
3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMi0xMjc/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd420fd55" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
brought a case</a> against a former Coinbase employee accusing him of insid=
er trading on some tokens that Coinbase listed. The SEC can only bring insi=
der trading cases about securities,=C2=A0and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/30935281.265435/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9saXRp=
Z2F0aW9uL2NvbXBsYWludHMvMjAyMi9jb21wLXByMjAyMi0xMjcucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cB30744e5e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;">it argued</a>=C2=A0that the tokens the guy traded =
were securities. I=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/30935281.265435/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9tYXR0X2xldmluZS9zdGF0dXMvM=
TU1MDIwMjAzNjU3MDAxNzc5Mg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB761a19e2" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">tweete=
d at the time</a>: =E2=80=9CThis is a weird way for the SEC to say that Coi=
nbase is running an illegal securities exchange?=E2=80=9D Sending Coinbase =
a Wells notice threatening to sue it for running an illegal securities exch=
ange would be a more normal way to say it, and here we are.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Taking a step back, though, if the SEC thinks =
that 90% of Coinbase=E2=80=99s crypto listings are illegal =E2=80=A6=C2=A0w=
hat took it so long? Coinbase has been running a crypto exchange <a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30935281.265435/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE2Nzk3ODgvMDAwMTYyODI4MDIxMDA2ODU=
wL2NvaW5iYXNlZ2xvYmFsaW5jNDI0Yi5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB765e067f" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;"> since 2012</a>, matching hundreds of billions of dollars of trades an=
d making billions of dollars of revenue. It has been, as crypto exchanges g=
o, pretty compliance-focused, getting various regulatory licenses (includin=
g an SEC broker-dealer license) and publishing audited financial statements=
. It is a US public company, listed on the Nasdaq; it went public in a dire=
ct listing in=C2=A02021. If Coinbase is running an illegal securities excha=
nge, it has been doing it out in the open for an awfully long time. Weird f=
or the SEC to only notice now.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so Coinbase Chief Executive Officer Brian =
Armstrong=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/309=
35281.265435/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9icmlhbl9hcm1zdHJvbmcvc3RhdHVzLzE2Mz=
g2NTQ0OTY4Nzk1NzUwNDA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc75a96b6" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">tweeted ab=
out the Wells notice</a>:<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important=
; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Two years ago the SEC reviewed our=
 business in detail and approved Coinbase to go public. Our S1 clearly expl=
ained our asset listing process and included 57 references to staking. Coin=
base runs a rigorous asset review process and has rejected more than 90% of=
 assets that have applied to be listed on the platform.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And Coinbase Chief Legal Officer Paul Grewal <=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30935281.265435/aHR=
0cHM6Ly93d3cuY29pbmJhc2UuY29tL2Jsb2cvd2UtYXNrZWQtdGhlLXNlYy1mb3ItcmVhc29uYW=
JsZS1jcnlwdG8tcnVsZXMtZm9yLWFtZXJpY2Fucy13ZS1nb3QtbGVnYWw/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cB6bfe4785" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;"> wrote a blog post</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SEC staff told us they have identified pot=
ential violations of securities law, but little more. We asked the SEC spec=
ifically to identify which assets on our platforms they believe may be secu=
rities, and they declined to do so. Today=E2=80=99s Wells notice also comes=
 after Coinbase provided multiple proposals to the SEC about registration o=
ver the course of months, all of which the SEC ultimately refused to respon=
d to. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Wells notice comes out of the investigatio=
n that we disclosed last summer. Shortly after that investigation began, th=
e SEC asked us if we would be interested in discussing a potential resoluti=
on that would include registering some portion of our business with the SEC=
. We said absolutely yes. Specifically, the SEC asked us to provide our vie=
ws on what a registration path for Coinbase could look like =E2=80=93 becau=
se there is no existing way for a crypto exchange to register. We developed=
 and proposed two different registration models. We spent millions of dolla=
rs on legal support to build these proposals and repeatedly asked for the S=
EC=E2=80=99s feedback. We got none. We also reiterated that we stand by our=
 listings process =E2=80=93 we don=E2=80=99t list securities today =E2=80=
=93 and repeatedly invited the SEC to raise any questions about any asset a=
t all on our platform. They raised none. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Regulatory uncertainty in the crypto industry =
is getting worse. Instead of developing a regulatory framework for crypto, =
the SEC is continuing to regulate by enforcement only.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I sympathize with all of this, and I have <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30935281.265435/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDktMDgvZ2FyeS1nZ=
W5zbGVyLXdhbnRzLXRvLXJlZ3VsYXRlLWNyeXB0bz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzIzMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVG=
RiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAzMjM=
mdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC5c9c13fe" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
>  written</a> similar <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/c=
lick/30935281.265435/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbG=
VzLzIwMjItMDktMTMvY3J5cHRvLXdhbnRzLXNvbWUtc2VjLXJ1bGVzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAzMjMyM=
19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90=
ZXJtPTIzMDMyMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB37f=
17f42" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;"> things</a>. It is truly hard to fit the particular features=
 of crypto into the existing US system for regulating securities, and a con=
scientious securities regulator with an interest in crypto regulation would=
 sit down and write rules explaining=C2=A0<em>how=C2=A0</em>a project could=
 register its crypto securities, how a crypto exchange could list crypto se=
curities, etc. (Obviously Coinbase=E2=80=99s proposal to write those rules=
=C2=A0<em>for=C2=A0</em>the SEC is kind of self-interested, but sure in gen=
eral regulation proceeds with industry input.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand I think that the SEC=E2=80=
=99s response is straightforward and obvious:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">There absolutely are existing, reason=
ably clear rules about how you register securities.</li>=09<li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;">Yes, you=E2=80=99re right, it=E2=80=99s impossible for cr=
ypto tokens to follow those rules.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"=
>Oh well! Guess that means crypto exchanges are illegal.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The position of Coinbase =E2=80=94=C2=A0and of=
 the crypto industry more broadly =E2=80=94=C2=A0is =E2=80=9Clook, SEC, if =
you want to have a flourishing system of legally compliant, safe, trustwort=
hy crypto assets, you will need to work with us a little bit to write new r=
ules,=E2=80=9D and the position of the SEC is =E2=80=9Cno, we don=E2=80=99t=
 want that, we want all of you to go away forever.=E2=80=9D If Bernie Madof=
f came to the SEC and said =E2=80=9Cif you want a higher class of more trus=
tworthy Ponzi schemes, you will need to write a few new rules adapting the =
disclosure regime to Ponzi schemes,=E2=80=9D the SEC would have said =E2=80=
=9Cno we absolutely do not want that, we want=C2=A0<em>much less </em>Ponzi=
 scheming, and we certainly do not want to give our=C2=A0<em>approval=C2=A0=
</em>to Ponzi schemes by writing rules for them.=E2=80=9D One gets the sens=
e the attitude to crypto is similar.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand Coinbase is an SEC-registere=
d public company with an SEC-registered broker-dealer license! The approval=
 is kind of already there! The SEC=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>attitude=C2=A0</em>to=
 crypto is extremely negative, but it is only slowly getting around to doin=
g anything about it =E2=80=94=C2=A0and in particular it is only slowly gett=
ing around to going after <em>big respectable</em> crypto firms like Coinba=
se. And in the interim, those firms have had time to get bigger and more re=
spectable, with the SEC=E2=80=99s quiet acquiescence.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here again I think the explanation is obvious =
but unsatisfying. I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/30935281.265435/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzL=
zIwMjMtMDItMTMvdGhlLXNlYy1jcmFja3MtZG93bi1vbi1jcnlwdG8_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMyMzIz=
X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3R=
lcm09MjMwMzIzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB26b4=
f654" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;">  wrote last month</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I submit to you that the main fact of crypto r=
egulation in early 2023 is that regulators feel really burned by the events=
 of 2022, and particularly by the collapse of FTX. =E2=80=9CWe want to work=
 with these nice smart young people who are building the financial system o=
f the future, and I am sure that with their advice we can write=C2=A0smart =
regulations=C2=A0that protect=C2=A0consumers while still fostering innovati=
on=E2=80=9D was a totally normal thing for regulators (except the SEC) to t=
hink and say in 2021. But now it is not! Now too many of those smart young =
people are under indictment or giving interviews from undisclosed locations=
; too much customer money is gone. If you run a crypto exchange and you wan=
t to set up a meeting with regulators to talk about how to write regulation=
s to prevent a repeat of the recent crypto collapses, they will not trust y=
ou, because=C2=A0<em>that is what FTX was saying too</em>. There is not muc=
h goodwill left. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When crypto is popular and exciting and going =
up, if you are a regulator who says =E2=80=9Cno, we must stop this,=E2=80=
=9D you look like a killjoy. Investors want to put their money into stuff t=
hat is going up, and they are mad at you for stopping them. Politicians lik=
e the stuff that is going up, and hold hearings about how you=E2=80=99re st=
ifling innovation. Crypto founders are rich and popular and criticize you o=
n Twitter and get a lot of likes and retweets. Your own regulatory employee=
s, who have an eye on their next private-sector jobs, want to be leaders in=
 crypto innovation rather than just banning everything.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When crypto is going down and so many projects=
 are evaporating in fraud and bankruptcy, you can kind of say =E2=80=9CI to=
ld you so.=E2=80=9D There is just a lot more appetite to regulate, or I gue=
ss just to shut everything down. =E2=80=9CYou are stifling innovation,=E2=
=80=9D the indicted founder of a bankrupt crypto firm can say, but nobody c=
ares.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is unsatisfying, first of all, from a rul=
e-of-law perspective: The SEC used a light touch in regulating crypto on th=
e way up, which encouraged a lot of companies (like Coinbase) to get into c=
rypto, invest a lot of resources, hire a lot of people and build big busine=
sses. (And which encouraged lots of people to <em>invest in crypto</em>, on=
 the theory that if it was really bad the SEC would have stopped it.) If th=
e SEC <em>now </em>says that was all illegal, it seems harsh and arbitrary.=
 As Armstrong says, the SEC had plenty of opportunities to object to Coinba=
se in the past; it didn=E2=80=99t, and Coinbase relied on the SEC=E2=80=99s=
 acceptance in building its business. The answer =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwe=
 <em>would</em> have objected in 2021, but crypto was cool then and people =
would have gotten mad at us for getting in the way, but now crypto is bad a=
nd we can do whatever we want=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0does not feel like gr=
eat regulatory procedure.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is also bad=C2=A0<em>substantive=C2=A0</em>=
regulation =E2=80=94=C2=A0bad consumer protection =E2=80=94=C2=A0to encoura=
ge crypto on the way up and crack down on after the crash. Stopping people =
from investing in crypto <em>after=C2=A0</em>they=E2=80=99ve lost all their=
 money doesn=E2=80=99t do them any good!=C2=A0You want to=C2=A0<em>stop=C2=
=A0</em>the crash! You want to =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/30935281.265435/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa=
2kvV2lsbGlhbV9NY0NoZXNuZXlfTWFydGlu/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1247b5dc" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;">take away the punch bowl just as the party gets going</a>,=E2=80=9D but=
 that is easy to say and hard, politically, to do. When the party is over a=
nd everyone is nursing a crushing hangover, no one cares what you do with t=
he punch bowl. =E2=80=9CUgh that punch bowl, get it out of here, what even =
was in that,=E2=80=9D they will retch.=C2=A0</p>
